{
  "_comment": "FIXTURE shape catalog — building pieces AND non-disguisable decoration. Kept SEPARATE from props.json on purpose: props.json is the disguise catalog (only genuinely movable items a player can hide as), and a fixture must never be disguisable. Fixtures are referenced ONLY from a map's fixtures[] array; the referee builds its disguise pool from map.props alone, so nothing here can ever become a disguise. Each entry keeps a primitive shape (fallback + GLB size target) plus a `model` GLB path; `modelSize` overrides the auto size target, and `modelDims`:{w,h,d} scales the GLB per-axis to EXACT world sizes for pieces whose native proportions don't match the intended footprint (floor tiles). scene.js merges this with props.json into one render lookup at match start.",

  "_comment_split": "STATIC/DYNAMIC SPLIT (physics fix #2): `\"static\": true` = genuinely bolted-in (floor, walls, pillars, doors, vent/hood, big built-ins: counters, cabinets, oven, fridge, sinks, shelves) — an immovable collider. `\"decor\": true` = tiny FIXED dressing (thin cut-food/garnish, lids, the shelf paper-towel) kept static on purpose: as dynamic bodies they'd form unstable micro-stacks or spawn inside a tall fixture's cuboid collider and get ejected. EVERYTHING ELSE here (no flag) is now a DYNAMIC, knockable rigid body — tables, cookware, plates, dishes, whole food, condiments — promoted into the referee's prop stream (non-disguisable). shared/physics.js#isStaticEntry is the single source of truth; scene.js + referee.js read the same flags.",

  "_comment_floor": "floor_kitchen: uses modelDims (non-uniform) so the checkerboard tile is forced to a thin 8x0.2x8 slab regardless of the GLB's native thickness.",
